MA]])\n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears  = 1985\u2013present\n|rank          = [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|commands      = [[371st Sustainment Brigade (United States)|371st Sustainment Brigade]]\n|mawards       = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br>[[File:Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service]]<br>[[File:Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]]<br>[[File:Army Reserve Achievement ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Reserve Good Conduct Medal|Reserve Good Conduct]]<br>[[File:National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|30px]] [[National Defense Service Medal]]\n}}\n'''Steven Ernst Stivers''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|t|a\u026a|v|\u0259r|z}} (born March 24, 1965) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|OH|15}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and became chair of the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] in 2017. Stivers previously served in the [[Ohio Senate]], representing the 16th district. He is a [[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier General]] in the [[Ohio Army National Guard]] and served [[active duty]] in [[Iraq]] as [[Battalion#United States Army and Marine Corps|Battalion]] [[Commanding officer|Commander]] until December 2005.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\n\nStivers was born and grew up in [[Ripley, Ohio]], the son of Carol Sue (n\u00e9e Pulliam) and Ernst Bambach Stivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/stivers.htm|title=Steve Stivers ancestry|publisher=|accessdate=January 1, 2016}}</ref> Steve is a recipient of the [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] Award.<ref name=\"trivillagerotary.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.trivillagerotary.org/Newsletters/2008/3-26-08.doc |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728130247/http://www.trivillagerotary.org/Newsletters/2008/3-26-08.doc |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nStivers attended The [[Ohio State University]] where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[economics]] and [[international relations]] in 1989 and an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1996.<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.stivers4congress.com/?q=biography Steve Stivers Biography]</ref> While attending Ohio State he joined the [[Delta Upsilon]] Fraternity.\n\nStivers spent seven years at [[Bank One]], three years at the Ohio Company, two years as Finance Director for the [[Franklin County, Ohio|Franklin County]] Republican Party and five years as a staff member in the [[Ohio Senate]].<ref name=about>{{cite web| title =Senator Steve Stivers \u2013 Website| work =| publisher =| date =| url =http://www.senatorstevestivers.com/index.php?id=33| doi =| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080411022148/http://www.senatorstevestivers.com/about/| archivedate =April 11, 2008| accessdate =2009-10-28| deadurl =yes| df =mdy-all}}</ref> Stivers has worked as a [[General Securities Representative Exam|Series 7]] licensed securities [[stockbroker|trader]] with the Ohio Company.<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\n==Military service==\nStivers has served in the [[Ohio Army National Guard]] since 1985 and holds the rank of Brigadier General in the [[United States Army Logistics Branch|Logistics branch]]. Stivers was called to [[active duty]] while serving in the Ohio Senate in October 2004. It was then that Stivers served in [[Iraq]], [[Kuwait]], [[Qatar]], and [[Djibouti]] as Battalion Commander until December 2005. He was awarded a [[Bronze Star]] for his accomplishments as a battalion commander during [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].<ref name=about/>\n\n==Ohio Senate==\n\n===Elections===\nIn December 2002, incumbent Republican [[Priscilla Mead]] decided to resign after only serving in the [[Ohio Senate]] for a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=cgskAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wxIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3556,12300&dq=priscilla+mead&hl=en|title=Westland News - Google News Archive Search|publisher=|accessdate=January 1, 2016}}</ref> Stivers was recommended by a Senate screening committee and was appointed by election of the Senate Republicans on January 4, 2003.  \nHe then won re-election in 2004 to a full senate term with 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=70709|title=Our Campaigns - OH State Senate 16 Race - Nov 02, 2004|publisher=|accessdate=January 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nStivers served in the [[Ohio Senate]] from January 9, 2003, until December 2008.\n\n===Committee assignments===\nStivers sat on a variety of Ohio Senate committees. He was the Chairman of the Insurance, Commerce and Labor Committee, Vice-Chair of the Finance and Financial Institutions Committee, served on the Ways and Means Committee, the Judiciary Committee on Civil Justice, the Judiciary Committee for Criminal Justice, and also the Controlling Board.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101223031058/http://www.freedomspeaks.com/official/63247/ohio-(oh)-state-senator-steve-stivers-%5Boh-senate%5D Freedom Speaks Official Profile]</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2008\n[[Image:StiversGrandviewParade.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Steve Stivers shaking hands at the Grandview Memorial Day Weekend Parade.]]\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2008#District 15}}\n\nIn November 2007, Stivers announced he would run for election to Congress in Ohio's 15th District, a seat held by retiring Republican member [[Deborah Pryce]]. He won the Republican nomination and ran against Democratic [[Franklin County, Ohio|Franklin]] [[Ohio county government#Board of County Commissioners|County Commissioner]] [[Mary Jo Kilroy]], who had nearly unseated Pryce in 2006, [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Mark Noble and Independent Don Elijah Eckhart. Stivers lost by 2,311 votes, conceding on December 7, 2008, after a long vote  recount.\n\n;2010\n[[File:Boehnerandstivers.jpg|thumb|[[John Boehner]], the then House Minority Leader, campaigning for fellow Ohio Congressman Steve Stivers (left) during the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2010|2010 midterm elections]]|right|alt=]]\n{{See also |United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2010#District 15*}}\n\nStivers won the Republican primary with 82% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vote.franklincountyohio.gov/assets/pdf/2010/primary/EL45A.HTM |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527232623/http://vote.franklincountyohio.gov/assets/pdf/2010/primary/EL45A.HTM |archivedate=May 27, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2010/05/05/copy/dailey-gibbs-fight-for-lead-in-gops-18th.html?adsec=politics&sid=101|title=Dispatch Politics|work=The Columbus Dispatch|accessdate=January 1, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510154825/http://www.dispatchpolitics.com/live/content/local_news/stories/2010/05/05/copy/dailey-gibbs-fight-for-lead-in-gops-18th.html?adsec=politics&sid=101|archivedate=May 10, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He again faced Democratic incumbent [[Mary Jo Kilroy]] along with Constitution Party nominee David Ryon and Libertarian nominee William J. Kammerer. On November 2, 2010, Kilroy conceded to Stivers, who won by a 54% to 42% margin.\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2012#District 15}}\nRedistricting after the 2010 census made the 15th much friendlier to Stivers. During his first term, he represented a fairly compact district covering all of [[Union County, Ohio|Union]] and [[Madison County, Ohio|Madison]] counties, as well as most of downtown and western Columubus. The new map, however, pushed the 15th into more rural and exurban territory south and west of the capital.\n\nStivers ran again in 2012 against Democratic nominee Pat Lang.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ohio Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/sos/upload/elections/2012/gen/UScongress.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118192227/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/sos/upload/elections/2012/gen/UScongress.pdf|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2012-11-18}}</ref>  He was endorsed by the NRA, National Right to Life, Ohio State Medical Association and United States Chamber of Commerce. Stivers was re-elected by 76,397 votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stivers for Congress|url=http://www.stivers4congress.com/endorsements|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007003219/http://www.stivers4congress.com/endorsements|archivedate=October 7, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Ohio, 2014#District 15}}\nStivers ran in 2014 against Democratic rival Scott Wharton. Gaining more than 66 percent of the vote, he was reelected for a third term.<ref>http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/Research/electResultsMain/2014Results.aspx</ref>\n\n;2016\n[[File:Steve Stivers District Office 1.jpg|thumb|Steve Stivers District Office in Hilliard, Ohio]]\nStivers ran in 2016 against Democrat Scott Wharton for the OH-15 seat. Winning 66.2% (222,847) of the vote to Wharton's 33.8% (113,960).<ref>https://ballotpedia.org/Ohio%27s_15th_Congressional_District</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n;Budget\nStivers has voted against raising the debt limit when there was no offset or systemic reform and supports prioritizing spending in the event that the debt limit is reached.<ref name=issues>{{cite web| title =Steve Stivers: (Republican, district 15) | work =On the Issues| url =http://www.ontheissues.org/OH/Steve_Stivers.htm}}</ref><ref name=votebudget>{{cite web| title =Representative Steve Stivers's Voting Records: Budget, Spending and Taxes| work =Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/45333/steve-stivers/10/budget-spending-and-taxes#.UcC4mvk3upo}}</ref>  He was part of a proposal to add a balanced budget amendment to the US Constitution.<ref name=issues/><ref name=votebudget/>  Stivers voted to offset the costs of disaster relief spending through discretionary budget cuts.<ref name=votebudget/>\n\nOn December 15, 2011, Stivers introduced a bill that would alter the composition of the [[Penny (United States coin)|penny]], [[Nickel (United States coin)|nickel]], [[Dime (United States coin)|dime]] and [[Quarter (United States coin)|quarter]] to [[steel]], with a [[copper]] coat for the penny, which claimed to save an estimated $433,000,000 over the course of ten years.  The bill was referred to committee and was rejected, but Stivers has resubmitted it twice more, once in April 2013 (again rejected in committee) and again in January 2015 (once more referred to committee).<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.516:Cents and Sensibility Act|author=GovTrack.us|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr516/text|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>  In spite of the US Mint releasing a technical report in December 2014 for its Alternative Metals Study in which it reported that steel is an unacceptable material for US coins (due to difficulty in minting, lack of security, and severe impact on both the public and the coin vending industry),<ref>{{cite web|title=Alternative Metals Study Technical Report, 2014 Biennial Report to the Congress|author=United States Mint|url=http://www.usmint.gov/about_the_mint/PDFs/2014-rd-biennial-report-appendix-4.pdf|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ksadjhf|author=coinnews.net|url=http://www.coinnews.net/2014/12/15/us-mint-not-recommending-new-coin-compositions/|accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> Stivers kept the wording of his bill identical to the previous two versions.\n\nHe voted to audit the Federal Reserve and its recent actions, specifically its involvement in mortgage loans.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Energy\nStivers supports all energy options, including green, nuclear, and clean coal and supports tax benefits for renewable energy usage.<ref name=issues/><ref name=voteeenergy>{{cite web| title =Representative Steve Stivers's Voting Records: Energy| work =Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/45333/steve-stivers/29/energy#.UcC8rvk3upo}}</ref>  However Stivers opposes federal regulations on efficiency standards<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Gun control\nStivers is a strong supporter of gun rights and opposes any limits to Second Amendment rights.<ref name=issues/>  He supports loosening regulations for interstate gun purchases and supports veterans registering unlicensed firearms acquired from outside the United States.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;National security\nStivers opposed President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a temporary ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \"While I agree with the President that we must improve our visa vetting process in order to better protect Americans, I believe the executive order risks violating our nation's values and fails to differentiate mainstream Islamic partners from radical Islamic terrorists \u2014 setting back our fight against radical Islam. I urge the Administration to quickly replace this temporary order with permanent improvements in the visa vetting process.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n;Social security\nStivers opposes the privatization of social security.<ref name=issues/>  In addition, he also opposes raising the retirement age from its current state.<ref name=issues/>\n\n;Taxes\nStivers took the Taxpayer Protection pledge, insuring he would not support any tax raises.<ref name=issues/>  He supports a flat federal tax rate across the board for all income brackets.<ref name=issues/>\n\n===Legislation===\nStivers was ranked as the 36th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the second most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Ohio) by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== National Republican Congressional Committee ===\nStivers beat Rep. [[Roger Williams (U.S. politician)|Roger Williams]] to be elected chair the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] on November 18, 2016. In his position to support Republican congressional candidates, Stivers said his goal is to \"defy history\" in protecting his party's majority in the House.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/news/national-govt--politics/gop-picks-ohio-rep-for-campaign-post/0Jhb3nwrJklO0crQShCiLN/|title=GOP picks Ohio Rep. for campaign post|last=Wehrman|first=Jessica|date=November 15, 2016|work=Dayton Daily News|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> In June 2018, Stivers did not denounce the use of hacked materials in election campaigns, saying that as chair of the National Republican Congressional Committee he wouldn't \"run down one of my candidates for using something that's in the public domain.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/07/politics/midterm-election-hack-dccc-nrcc-meeting/index.html|title=House Dem, GOP campaign chiefs clash over using hacked materials in midterms|last=CNN|first=Eric Bradner,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-06-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Candidate conduct ====\nIn response to congressional candidate [[Greg Gianforte]] being charged with [[assault]] on the eve of [[Montana|Montana's]] [[Montana's at-large congressional district special election, 2017|special election]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missoulian.com/news/government-and-politics/gianforte-cited-for-misdemeanor-assault-allegedly-body-slammed-reporter/article_f5b0749d-62e1-517b-873a-3602bb3560bb.html|title=Gianforte cited for misdemeanor assault; allegedly body-slammed reporter|last=Fraser|first=Jayme|date=May 24, 2017|work=Missoulian|access-date=2017-05-25|last2=Lee Newspapers Staff|first2=|language=en}}</ref> Stivers characterized the assault as \"out of character.\" He said, \"we all make mistakes\" and \"need to let the facts surrounding this incident unfold.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/nrcc-chair-on-greg-gianforte-body-slam-was-totally-out-of-character-but-we-all-make-mistakes/article/2624146|title=NRCC chair on Greg Gianforte: Body slam 'was totally out of character, but we all make mistakes'|last=Weaver|first=Al|date=May 25, 2017|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=2017-05-25|language=en}}</ref> The assault was witnessed by four [[Fox News]] reporters and the victim's account corroborated by their audio recording.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/us/politics/greg-gianforte-montana-republican-body-slams-reporter.html|title=Montana Republican Greg Gianforte, Charged With Assault, Awaits Fate in Vote|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=2017-05-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-25|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Committee on Rules]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Republican Main Street Partnership]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n|-bgcolor=#cccccc\n!colspan=24 style=\"background: #ccccff;\" |Election results<ref>{{cite news| first =| last =| title =Election Results| date =| url =http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx| work =Ohio Secretary of State| accessdate =2014-03-01| deadurl =yes| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120815184807/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/elections/Research/electResultsMain.aspx| archivedate =August 15, 2012| df =mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year\n!Office\n!Election\n!\n!Subject\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!\n|-\n|2004\n|[[Ohio Senate]]\n|[[General election (U.S.)|General]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Steve Stivers'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |95,251